            <p>May <del>18</del> B 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Dr de Sola Mendes<lb/></p>
            <p>May 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>To Rev. Dr. de Sola Mendes<lb/>
                My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Let a pressure of occupations of a melancholy<lb/> nature&#44; and many private <sic>concersn</sic> be my apology for a<lb/> seeming neglect.  I regret that I <sic>acnnot</sic> atone for a delay in ack&#45;<lb/>knowledging receipt of your three communications<lb/> by <sic>agrreeing</sic> to your wish......<lb/></p>
            <p>With regard to my endorsing the Prayer book&#44; I<lb/> make bold to say&#44; that early training habits&#44; prejudice<lb/> if you will&#44; stand in the way.  You may have seen translat&#45;<lb/>ions of all our prayers in Spanish. They were for private<lb/> use among our women.  Only some of the Haftaroth being<lb/> publicly translated.  I have also books of prayers of a<lb/> character somewhat similar to yours&#44; not so extensive&#44;<lb/> in modern languages&#44; and I have lent them out on special<lb/> occasions.  You no doubt possess some of them.  But while<lb/> I admit that something ought to be done to awaken a spirit<lb/> of devotion&#44; and home is the fittest place to arouse it.  I<lb/> fear to offend my first love&#95;the Hebrew&#44; by recommending<lb/> a book which may still further supplant it.  Pardon the<lb/> freedom&#44; and please let not the public know that I have<lb/> thus taken it<lb/></p>
            </body>
